definition: "The thyroid gland produces two principal hormones: thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3). T4 is the primary secretory product of the thyroid — approximately 80% of thyroid hormone output is T4, with only about 20% secreted as the more active T3. Most T4 is a prohormone that must be converted to T3 in peripheral tissues (liver, kidney, muscle) by deiodinase enzymes before it can exert biological effects. T3 is the biologically active form — it binds to thyroid hormone receptors in the nucleus of virtually every cell in the body, regulating gene expression for hundreds of metabolic processes. In the bloodstream, over 99% of T3 and T4 are bound to carrier proteins (thyroid-binding globulin, albumin, and transthyretin), rendering them biologically inactive. Only the unbound — 'free' — fractions are biologically active and can enter cells. Free T4 (FT4) reflects thyroid production and reserves, while Free T3 (FT3) reflects the active hormone available at the tissue level. Standard thyroid testing with TSH alone measures only the pituitary's response to thyroid hormone levels — not the hormones themselves."
why_it_matters: "TSH (thyroid-stimulating hormone) is the workhorse of standard thyroid screening and is appropriate as a first-line test because it reflects the pituitary's integrated assessment of thyroid hormone adequacy. But TSH has a structural limitation: it measures the pituitary's perception of thyroid hormone status, not the actual hormones available to peripheral tissues. A TSH in the normal range does not guarantee that Free T3 and Free T4 are at levels associated with optimal metabolic function. This gap is clinically significant in several common scenarios: people converting T4 to T3 inefficiently due to selenium deficiency, chronic inflammation, or genetic deiodinase polymorphisms; people on T4-only thyroid replacement (levothyroxine) who may have normalized TSH and FT4 but have relatively low FT3 due to conversion limitations; and people with tissue-level hypothyroidism from elevated thyroid binding globulin that reduces the free fraction while keeping total T3/T4 normal. In longevity medicine, optimizing Free T3 specifically — the active hormone — is increasingly recognized as important for metabolic rate, cardiac function, body composition, and cognitive performance."

